@maxtepkeev Thanks for the detailed response. Sorry it has taken me soooo long to get back to you. I've read through your answer and I agree if end users only upgrade `python-redmine` and never upgrade `python-requests` then they will be insecure and likely end up with broken software. This would especially happen if changes in `python-redmine` require a specific version of `python-requests` and the user upgrades one without the other. Given that I can see how carrying it a resolution to that problem, but I think there is another way.

Setuptools supports [dependency declaration](http://pythonhosted.org/setuptools/setuptools.html#declaring-dependencies) using the `install_requires` mechanism. This way when users `pip install python-redmine` or `python setup.py install` from a checked out version of `python-redmine`, their dependencies will be upgraded with it. The current [setup.py on master](https://github.com/maxtepkeev/python-redmine/blob/master/setup.py#L55-L88) doesn't use `install_requires`. If that were added, I think the issue of upgrading `python-redmine` to version X and having any dependency version X requires such as `python-requests` being at a minimum version Y would be a non-issue.

What do you think about using that to manage dependencies instead of carrying internal versions of them?

@maxtepkeev this response is in the spirit of collaboration and improvement. I appreciate how much you've put into thinking about this issue and writing out your thoughts.

@jrief after analyzation of your code, my solution was achieved by a signal.
I know that my case is very special and it is complicated to cover all cases.

Thanks for your time!

```python
@receiver(post_save, sender=ShowcaseStatus)
@receiver(post_save, sender=ShowcaseFeatured)
@receiver(post_save, sender=ShowcaseDynamic)
@receiver(post_save, sender=ShowcaseAd)
def override_sort(sender, instance, created, **kwargs):
    if hasattr(instance, '_avoid_signal'):
        return

    instance._avoid_signal = True
    try:
        if created or instance.index == 0:
            next_index = Showcase.objects.aggregate(Max('index'))['index__max']
            instance.index = next_index + 1
            instance.save()

    finally:
        del instance._avoid_signal
```

