but this is still pointless:
in generalm programming, in function:
atreceive(ATCAIface ca_iface, uint8_t *rxdata, uint16_t *rxlength);
parameter rxlength usually act as an output to return actual bytes we read;
But:
1. for TWI,in fact we clock in whatever on the SDA when reading(iic bus),so actual rxlength is just rxdata[0]; 

2. for SWI,if actual read length was out of range( less than expected length in rxdata[0]),there were also codes dealling with these cases and return an error at the end of swi_receive_bytes():
if (status == ATCA_RX_TIMEOUT)
    {
        if (i > 0)
        {
            //! Indicate that we timed out after having received at least one byte.
            status = ATCA_RX_FAIL;
        }
    }
ATCA_RX_FAIL          : means we received insufficient bytes;
ATCA_RX_TIMEOUT  : means we received nothing;

so,
1. in hal_i2c_receive() and hal_swi_receive(),just using "rxlength" as an input,indicating max buffer size for safe operation is OK;
   to Keep the interface consistent,rxlength can also be a pointer;
   in these 2 functions,remove local variable "uint16_t rxdata_max_size;"  and it's codes;
2. in the whole library,keeping packet.data[ATCA_COUNT_IDX] as returned length under condition of "status==ATCA_SUCCESS" is recommended 
3. in atca_execute_command(),remove local variable "uint16_t rxsize;" since "pointless to Check response size" as mentioned above;

