} 
```
Which might lead to no `rval` being chosen. Although I'm not sure what are the chances that this statement will be true for all the entries from the cache, if it is, `kThreadError_NoBufs` will be returned, which will cause the packet being dropped in `MeshForwarder::GetDirectTransmission()`:
```
switch (error)
        {
        case kThreadError_None:
            ExitNow();

        case kThreadError_AddressQuery:
            mSendQueue.Dequeue(*curMessage);
            mResolvingQueue.Enqueue(*curMessage);
            continue;

        case kThreadError_Drop:
        case kThreadError_NoBufs:                 <<<=== Here it's being dequeued and disposed of
            mSendQueue.Dequeue(*curMessage);
            curMessage->Free();
            continue;
```
I was just wondering if a manual look up should be performed in this case?

Good catch! It looks like in this case both remote functions are identified by the name `__main__.func` and hence have the same function IDs. It seems like this is a problem that would only occur when a method of a class is decorated.

I haven't really thought much about that use case. Do you have a situation where decorating a method of a class like that is a natural thing to do?

One workaround that works is to do the following.

```python
import ray
import inspect

ray.init()

class A(object):
    def func(self):
        return inspect.getframeinfo(inspect.currentframe()).lineno

class B(object):
    def func(self):
        return inspect.getframeinfo(inspect.currentframe()).lineno

@ray.remote
def t1():
    return A.func(None)

@ray.remote
def t2():
    return B.func(None)

print(ray.get(t1.remote()))
print(ray.get(t2.remote()))
```

