@jvanasco Analyzing the certificates themselves should be relatively trivial, and using the certificates directly instead of a text file would prevent errors, like missing files, altered files, bad permissions, or even program errors. This is also not likely to be a command you're going to be executing frequently for the efficiency to really be much of a consideration. I would assume in the vast majority of cases it's only going to be executed when manually making changes to the certificates.

I would also actually disagree with your point about portability. I think the most portable thing is to only pass around the certificate file, not a certificate file and an additional text file containing the certificate "metadata" that are also contained in the certificate itself.

Just my $0.02.

